      "role": "system",
      "content": "You are an adaptive remediation agent on Rocky Linux / RHEL. Use tools to inspect and remediate the finding.\nSTRATEGY:\n1. ALWAYS read the relevant config file FIRST with read_file before making changes.\n2. Identify the exact key/value that needs changing.\n3. Use write_file for config changes (avoids shell quoting issues) or run_cmd for sed/systemctl.\n4. Verify with run_cmd (e.g. grep) that the change took effect.\n5. Call scan to confirm the fix.\nRULES:\n- One command at a time. Do NOT chain with && or ;\n- This is Rocky Linux/RHEL. Use dnf (not apt). Use systemctl (not service).\n- Do NOT duplicate config lines. If a key already exists, modify it in-place with sed.\n- If a key is commented out (# minlen = 8), uncomment and set the correct value.\n- stderr may contain SSH banners \u2014 ignore them. Check exit_code and stdout for results."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "You are the Remedy agent remediating ONE OpenSCAP finding on Rocky Linux 10.\nYou MUST use ONLY the provided tools: run_cmd, read_file, write_file, scan.\nRules:\n- Use run_cmd for EXACTLY ONE shell command at a time. Do NOT chain with && ; or multiline scripts.\n- Commands run as root. Do not prefix with sudo.\n- ALWAYS use read_file to inspect the target config file BEFORE modifying it.\n- Do NOT append duplicate lines. Use sed -i to modify existing values in-place.\n- If a line is commented (e.g. '# minlen = 8'), uncomment it and set the value.\n- Prefer minimal, reversible changes and verify with scan at the end.\n\nFINDING:\n- Title: Verify Permissions on /var/log Directory\n- Rule Name: file_permissions_var_log\n- Rule ID: xccdf_org.ssgproject.content_rule_file_permissions_var_log\n- Finding ID: openscap_040\n- Severity: 2\n- Host: localhost\n\nTRIAGE CONTEXT:\n- Approved for remediation because: Changing permissions on /var/log directory is a low-risk operation and is unlikely to lock out access\n- Description: To properly set the permissions of /var/log, run the command: $ sudo chmod 0755 /var/log\n- Recommendation: Remediation script: find -H /var/log/ -maxdepth 0 -perm /u+s,g+ws,o+wt -type d -exec chmod u-s,g-ws,o-wt {} \\;\n\nREVIEW FEEDBACK (apply improvements):\nQA validation error: name 'datetime' is not defined Suggestions: Implement the full find-based command to explicitly remove setuid, setgid, and sticky bits as intended.; Use a more robust script that checks current permissions before modifying them.; Avoid redundant no-op commands to improve clarity and reduce error surface.\n\nSTRUCTURED REVIEW HISTORY (address these specific issues):\n  Review #1: approve=True, score=9\n    Concerns: The remediation only sets generic 0755 permissions without addressing the specific umask or special bits mentioned in the original recommendation.; Repeated chmod commands with empty entries indicate inefficient scripting.\n    Required improvements: Implement the full find-based command to explicitly remove setuid, setgid, and sticky bits as intended.; Use a more robust script that checks current permissions before modifying them.; Avoid redundant no-op commands to improve clarity and reduce error surface.\n    Feedback: The fix successfully removed the reported issue, but the method is overly simplistic and does not precisely target the special permission bits described in the recommendation.\n\nPREVIOUS ATTEMPTS (1):\n* Attempt 1: success=False scan_passed=False\n  Commands:\n    - \n    - chmod 0755 /var/log\n    - \n    - \n  Scan output: Vulnerability openscap_040 not found in single-rule scan (possibly fixed)\n\nReturn tool calls as needed. End by calling scan."
